{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937113001/0976.xml":{"full_text":"It Was F. D.'s Score, but the\nTunes Were Herb's and Cal's\nBy RAYMOND CLAPPER\nSomething tells me this is the wrong way to put it, but it\ndoes seem as if in dealing with the business recession Presi\ndent Roosevelt is growing more like Hoover every day. The\nonly excuse for saying it that way, at the risk of creating ap\nprehension among some, is to emphasize again that Roosevelt\nis no revolutionary nor a collectivist, but a good friend, if a\nsevere critic, of the private capitalist sys\nhmg.s tem.\nass. Roosevelt's housing message might well\nssammg: have come from the hand of Hoover him\nself.\nHere is no Federal scoop-shovel\n\nspending proposal. There isn't a white\nrabbit in the whole message. It is quite\ndull.\nRoosevelt proposes that the Fed\nClapper\neral Government give encouragement to\nprivate business, that it throw its guar\nI antee behind private construction enter\nI prises, help reduce financing costs, and\nI try to make it more practicable \u201cfor pri\nl vate enterprises to engage in large-scale\nhousing operations for the mass market.\u201d\nHe doesn\u2019t propose that the Government\ncompete with private enterprise, nor supplant it. On the con\ntrary, he offers the old reliable Coolidge-Hoover formula\u2014\nstand behind business and help it go ahead with the job.\nAlong with this, Roosevelt has offered other aids, all equally\northodox. There are the business conferences, the appeals lor\nco-operation of industry and labor, and the eminently respect\nHe is asking Con\nable proposal for Government economy.\ngress to curtail highway expenses. Think of that. Roosevelt\nproposing to cut down road expenditures in the best Coolidge\ntradition: And he wants to balance the budget. That is be\ncoming an obsession with him, as it was with Hoover in the\nearly 30s.\nSecretary Morgenthau, intimate of the President. made a\nspeech recently' sternly demanding Government economy and a\nbalanced budget, but his audience couldn\u2019t believe he meant it.\nRoosevelt himself has taken up the issue, and while he prob\nably recognizes that it will be impossible to balance the budget\nwithin the next year or two, he thinks it desirable to keep\nThat is the significant thing.\nup a fight for it.\nThis is a most complete and fundamental reversal of a basic\nNew Deal principle\u2014that the Government should spend in\ntimes of receding business activity and curtail with recovery\u2014\nonly, when times improved, It forgot to do anything about the\nlatter half of the principle. The only concession Roosevelt\nhas made thus far toward the spending theory is his move\nto bunch Government purchases of supplies and distribute the\norders now instead of spreading them over the remainder of\nthe fiscal year. That involves no increase in expenditure.\nThus as you look at Washington now, you see Roosevelt\nplaying the role created in 1929 by Hoover. The only differ\nence is that Roosevelt plays it with a little more verve. The\nlines are the same, only brightened up with the Roosevelt per\nsonality.\nNaturally left-wingers in the Administration don't like the\ncourse Roosevelt is taking.\nIt makes obsolete a great many\ntheses which had been written in defense of the New Deal\nspending theory. They say that Roosevelt is applying economy\ntreatment at the wrong time, that housing will get nowhere\nwithout real Government spending.\nThey want to use the\nSocial Security reserve to prime the housing program. But for\nthe moment at least, they are not being listened to.\nRoosevelt has been pounded so hard by critics of Federal\nspending that he evidently has determined to let business do\nits stuff. He is settling down to try out the remedies which\nthe business world has clamored for so heatedly\u2014economy, cur\ntailment of spending, and giving business a chance to go under\nits own steam. The professors, the theorists who \u201cnever met a\npay roll.\u201d and all of the New Deal thinkers get a breathing\nspell. The New Deal is suspended while the piactical men try\ntheir hand.\nYou can imagine Roosevelt down off the coast of Florida\nfishing among the sharks and saying to himself: \"All right.\nI\u2019ll try their way a while and see how it comes out.\u201d\nNow here's a chance for the Liberty League to come back to\nlife and show what it can do in a really constructive way.\nIt Seems to Me\nBy Heywood\nBROUN\nTT IS surprising to learn that Har\nvard made money during the\nfiscal year of 1936-37. The amount\nwas hardly sufficient to make a divi\ndend payment likely. To be precise\nthe income was $10,272,341 and the\nBroun\nexpenses $10,246,\n929.\nAnd that\nleaves, as nearly\nas I can figure\nit in my head,\n$25,412 to be set\ndown\nblack.\nin\nthe\nAt the\nsame time the\nbook\nvalue\nof\nfunds rose from\n$134,000,000 to al\nmost $142,000,000.\nObviously the\nuniversity is big\nbusiness and a\ngoing concern.\nAltho the profit represents a\nsmall return on the invested capi\ntal, it is disturbing to find education\nyielding any financial return what\nsoever. In my undergraduate days\nit was frequently pointed out to me\nthat Harvard was spending three\ntimes as much for my training as I\nwas contributing.\nIt has always\nseemed to me that it was a bad\nbargain for both of us.\nBut the immediate point is what\nshould the university do with the\n$25,000 surplus with which it is\nstuck.\nA\nFEW years ago the answer\nwould have been easy. It was\nthen that Lucius Beebe, an under\ngraduate, suggested that Harvard\nsend Yale three professors and $50.\n000 in exchange for a backfield.\nBill McGeehan publicized the plan\nand I believe the proposal was car\nried almost two to one in a refer\nendum of the student body. Noth\ning was done about it at the time.\nNow Harvard has a backfield, or\nat least it had one in the closing\nStill, another\ngame against Yale.\nseason looms ahead, and no one can\nquite laugh off the suggestion that\nthe 25 grand be entrusted to Dick\nHarlow as foundation for a Har\nvard School of Acting and Sleight\nof-Hand in which another Vernon\nStruck might be developed. It is\npertinent to remember that the\nCrimson\u2019s great spinning\ncarrier\nwas half football player and half\ndistinguished thespian. He was a\ncombination of Albee and Edwin\nBooth, retaining the best features\nof each.\nIn spite of its rigid amateurism,\nacademic Harvard is beginning to\nlag behind athletic Harvard.\nNo\nsurplus should lie idle until one of\nConant\u2019s\ncouriers has discovered\nsomebody who can teach philosophy\none-half so well as Richard Harlow\nteaches footbail.\nCopyright, 1937\nBAD HUMOR\nBy DAN KIDNEY\nEurope is a land filled with\nstrained relations.\nWonder if young Mussolini would\nthink war \"beautiful\u201d if he had been\nin the Ethiopian army?\nCongress had better be working on\nthe answer to this question: \u201cWhat\nwere you doing while I was in\nFlorida?\u201d\nAnother difficulty is that so many\ntax reformers don\u2019t seem to favor\nany other reformation.\nSIDE GLANCES\nby George Clark\n\u2018Listen, Doctor, we\u2019re afraid he has swallowed the page that\ntells what to do if he should swallow something.\u201d\nNew Deal Has to Be Started\nOver Again, Says McCowan\nBy REV. FATHER R. A. McGOWAN\nOne of the quasi-New Deal papers\neditorially asks for modifications in\nthe regulations of business to allow\n\u201ca reasonable expectation of satis\nfactory profits\" and then publishes\non a remote page in fine print cur\nrent declarations of seven accumu\nlated dividends. 14 extra dividends,\nsix increased dividends, one initial\ndividend, one irregular dividend, one\nliquidating dividend, three stock divi\ndends, one special dividend, one re\nsumed dividend, and 65 regular divi\ndends. Here are 10 kinds of profits\nand not one of them, I suppose, \"sat\nisfactory.\u201d\nJust what are satisfactory profits?\nThey cannot be satisfactorily high\nenough to please\nthe investor. The\ninvestor\u2019s pleas\nure in this re\nMcGowan\nspect\nroof.\nhas\nno\nInstead\neven tried to have them.\nthey have to be\nsatisfactorily low\nenough to keep\nthe whole coun\ntry employed.\nMani f e s 11 y we\nhave n\u2019t been\nhaving that kind\never. Manifestly,\ntoo, we haven't\nMani\nfestly, too, we have tried for the\nVery opposite kind.\nPROFITS SHOULD BE LOW\nProfits have to be low because\nthe profit-takers are too few and\nthe chief profit-takers far too few\nto use the big profits after they\nget them.\nThey get big profits\nfrom high prices, from low wages\nand low salaries and from high\ntaxes on the poor and people of\nmoderate means. When they get\nthe big profits, they cannot con\nceivably buy goods with them be\ncause they cannot use the goods\nand if they invest in new means of\nproducing more goods the people\nin general cannot buy goods enough\nto keep either the new or the old\nmeans of production working. And\nso the people get no work. There\nis nothing mysterious\nn bout it.\nEveryone knows it.\nNo wonder there is business re\ncession again. A large part of the\nnew employment of the past year\nhas not been due at all to a better\ndistribution of the country\u2019s goods\nthru a better distribution of the\ncountry's income. It has been due\nto the sale abroad of war supplies.\nThe fact of the matter is that we\nhave to start the New Deal over\nagain,\nThis business recession to still\nlower depths of depression has\nevoked loud and raucous cries and\nalso suave whisperings against all\nthat has been done and all that\nthis Congress was called to do. It\nhas evoked further cries against\norganized labor and laughter at the\nfarmers' organizations. Because war\nsupplies are not being bought as\nmuch and the income of the coun\ntry hasn\u2019t been distributed widely\nenough, business and employment\ngo down. And yet the very means\nof getting a better distribution of\nincome are widely attacked, and\nthe very means of preventing a\ngood distribution are widely de\nfended.\nCo-operation of business and Gov\nernment is asked. That means fur\nther governmental license to busi\nness. Instead, business, labor, farm\ners and Government should co-op\nerate.\nGrowth of the unions gives\nthis a better chance than in '33.\nIn the co-operation mistakes will\ncome.\nBut at any rate they will\nbe mistakes in attempts to do right\nand not the essential and eternal\nevil of trying, as now, to do wrong.\nPROMPT ACTION AT GLENN DALE\nADULT patients have been transferred from Gler.n Dale\nTuberculosis Sanatorium for Children, pending what\nHealth Officer George C. Ruhland has called a \u201cthrashing out\u201d\nof this question of policy by a group of Health Department\nadvisers from the ranks of prominent local physicians.\nIt is a question which should be settled only after a careful\ninspection of the physical layout of the sanatorium building.\nEven if there are empty beds, they should not be filled with\nadult patients who have what doctors call \u201copen\u201d cases of dis\nease, if facilities are such that the proximity of those open\ncases will endanger children with less serious infection.\nThe News, in an exclusive story, last week pointed out that\nadults and children were being housed in the same building,\nand their prompt removal followed.\nWhether or not the condition could be overcome by complete\nsegregation on separate floors of the children s institution, is\na matter for administrative planning.\nMeanwhile, it is gratifying that the two classes of patients\nhave been separated until the problem has been thoroly\nstudied by experts.\nPlain Economics\nby John T. Flynn\nNEW YORK\u2014I suppose it is safe to say now that it is in\nagain\u2014I mean the dollar.\nThere comes a point as soon as things begin to get a little\nbad when those who believe that prosperity is created by\nhigher prices and higher prices are created by Government\nmoney, rise in their places and demand that the presses be\noiled.\nThe business index, which reached\nits high, since the depression be\ngan, only a few months ago, has\nbeen descending for less than 12\nweeks.\nBut already a Senate com\nmittee\u2014the Agricultural Committee\u2014\nFlynn\nhas brought in a\nreport that we\nstart monkeying\nwith the dollar\nagain.\nThe President\nhas just declared\nthat\nwe\nmust\nhave an investi\ngation of high\nprices. The Sen\nate Agricultural\nCommittee\nan\nnounces to the\nSenate\nthat\nnot\nprices\nare\nhigh enough. They must be pushed\nup until they reach the 1926 level.\nTire committee demands that this\nbe done by fooling with the dollar.\nIt wants the Government to \"stabil\nize\u201d the dollar at the 1926 level.\nAnd the way to do this, of course,\nis to issue some more dollars and\nkeep on issuing them until prices\nhit the 1926 point. Of course what\nthey are most interested in is farm\nprices,\nraising\ngo up.\nThis\nBut if you attempt price\nwill\nthis way all prices\nis the remedy which the\nagrarians began to yell for in the\nearly days of\nHoover's troubles.\nFinally by 1932 they succeeded so\nfar as to pass the Goldsborough bill\nthru the House with only a few\u2014\nI think eight\u2014dissenting votes. That\nwas a bill to stabilize the dollar by\ncentering all money authority in a\nsingle agency which would direct\nthe Federal Reserve Board to issue\ndollars until prices went to the 1926\nThat bill was passed but\nlevel.\ndidn\u2019t get by the other house.\nThen came Mr. Roosevelt and\nSen. Thomas launched again his\nclamor for Government-issued dol\nlars. The inflationists thought that\nby issuing a few billion dollars the\n1926 price level could be reached.\nThe dollar printing scheme was not\naccepted. But one quite as effective\nand of the same general character\nwas adopted\ndollars\nbonds\nInstead of punting\nthe Government printed\nand\nTreasury notes and\nflooded them into the banks. This\nwas inflation just as much and\nmuch easier to put over than print\ning dollars.\nInstead of flooding a\nfew billions the Government has\nflooded 18 billions of this kind of\nmoney into our system since Mr.\nThomas made his demand in 1833.\nBut we haven\u2019t hit the 1926 level yet.\nWe have put prices up. And al\ntho they haven't hit the 1926 level\nthe economic society has already be\ngun to gag and to regurgitate the\nprice-raising policy. Prices have al\nready canceled purchasing power to\nthe point where we are on the way\ndown again.\nSo now the dollar issuers are in\nagain. Once again I suggest that it\nlooks very much as if this were\nthe first step of an attempt to\nspend the gold profit.\nCopyriht, 1937\nA Bit More Stoicism\nIs What Car Riders\nNeed, Says This One\nEditor. The News:\nH\nAVI NG seen our street ear sys\ntem evolve from ill smelling,\nrickety Toonerville\nslow-moving.\ntypes of vehicle to swift, electrically\nheated busses and \"streamliners,' I\nam at a loss to understand the cur\nlent squawks about service.\nI wonder what tne moderns would\nhave done if they had lived in the\n90s when the only warmth in street\ncars was from a layer of straw un\nder the feet? People took life as it\ncame and hardships were accepted\nNor did they\nwithout a murmur.\nexpect \"de luxe\u201d service when the\nfare was only, a few pennies. How\ntimes have hanged!\nVETERAN RIDER.","height":"21208","width":"14548"}}
